Introduction¶

We continue our analysis of the healthcare provider dataset containing data on discharges, payments, coverage and medicare payments for 163,065 provider-disease group combinations.

Data Preparation¶

We load and prepare the data based on previous week's findings. We perform the following steps:

  • Load data
  • Convert appropriate variables into float and strong types
  • Rename columns to follow convention, and enable easier code blocks
  • Create one additional variable for Average out of pocket payments (average_pocket_paments)

#Understanding the data
#Converting necessary columns into numeric floats
data[' Average Total Payments '] = data[' Average Total Payments '].str.extract(r'(\d+.\d)').astype('float')
data[' Average Covered Charges '] = data[' Average Covered Charges '].str.extract(r'(\d+.\d)').astype('float')
data['Average Medicare Payments'] = data['Average Medicare Payments'].str.extract(r'(\d+.\d)').astype('float')
data['Provider Id'] = data['Provider Id'].astype(str)

data.rename(columns = { "DRG Definition": "DRG_def", "Provider Id": "provider_id", "Provider Name": "provider_name", "Provider Street Address": "provider_street",
                       "Provider City": "provider_city", "Provider State": "provider_state", "Provider Zip Code": "provider_zip",
                       "Hospital Referral Region Description": "hospital_referral_region", " Total Discharges ": "total_discharges", 
                       " Average Covered Charges ": "average_covered_charges", " Average Total Payments ": "average_total_payments",
                      "Average Medicare Payments": "average_medicare_payments"}, errors = "raise", inplace = True)

#Calculating out-of-pocket expenses
data['average_pocket_payments'] = data['average_total_payments'] - data['average_medicare_payments']

Basic Ratios¶

Based on our preliminary resarch and the models identified in current research, we create the following ratios:

  • Medicare payments to Total Payments - Typically, Medicare covers about 80% of total payments
  • Medicare payments to covered charges - Ideally, average medicare payments should equal or be less than covered charges
  • Total payments to covered charges
  • Out-of-pocket payments to Medicare Payments

These ratios are widely used within the industry, in addition to identifying abnormallyhigh payments or number of discharges to identify fraud.

In [4]:
#Adding additional data columns to enable factor engineering

data['medicare_by_total'] = (data['average_medicare_payments'] / data['average_total_payments'])
data['medicare_by_covered'] = (data['average_medicare_payments'] / data['average_covered_charges'])
data['total_by_covered'] = (data['average_total_payments'] / data['average_covered_charges'])
data['oop_by_medicare'] = (data['average_pocket_payments'] / data['average_medicare_payments'])

Correlation Filtering¶

Now that we have identified provider, disease group, state, city and referral region as a factor affecting total discharges and average medicare payments. We can begin creating features that use these characterestics. However, first we need to remove variables in the current dataset which are correlated with each other.

In [16]:
corr = data.corr()
plt.figure(figsize = (10,10))
mask = np.triu(np.ones_like(corr, dtype = bool ))
cmap = sns.diverging_palette(230, 20,  as_cmap = True)
sns.heatmap(corr, mask = mask, cmap = cmap, square = True, annot= True, vmax= 0.5, vmin = -0.5, center= 0.00)
plt.title('Correlation Plot for Base variables and Ratios')
Out[16]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Correlation Plot for Base variables and Ratios')

Based on the above correlation plot, we will drop the following factors which show a high correlation (Greater than 0.7 or Less than -0.7) to one or more other factors:

  • Average Total Payments (High positive correlation to Average medicare payments and Average covered charges)
  • Average Covered Charges (High postive correlation to Average medicare payments)
  • Ratio of Total Payments to Covered Charges (High positive correlation to ratio of medicare payments to covered charges)
  • Ratio of Out of pocket payments to medicare payments (High negative correlation to ratio of medicare payments to total payments)

Feature Engineering¶

Calculating Benchmarks¶

The first step in our feature engineering journey is to create benchmarks for the variables associated with each observation, which we identified earlier:

  • Provider (Identified by ID)
  • Disease Group (DRG)
  • City in which the provider is (Provider_City)
  • State in which the provider is (Provider_State)
  • Hospital Referral Region which the provider is part of (Hospital_referral_region)

For each of these groups to which the provider belongs we calculated the following benchmarks:

  • Median
  • Standard Deviation

Benchmarks for were calculated for the following measures:

  • Total Discharges
  • Average Medicare Payments
  • Average Out of Pocket Payments
  • Ratio of medicare payments to covered charges
  • Ratio of mediare payments to total payments

As can be seen above, we followed a simple naming convention for the benchmarks created.

The first word would signify the measure (mean or standard deviation), followed one to two words signifying the aggregation level (For example, provider or DRGxState) and the last word would signify the variable (For exampple, td means total discharges). Simply,

  • sd_drg_mbc : Standard deviation for Medicare payments by Covered Charges for each DRG

And so on.

In this manner, we have summary statistics across the following aggregations:

  • Single level
    • Provider
    • State
    • City
    • Disease group
  • Dual level
    • Disease group and State
    • Disease group and referral group

Each of these aggregations will serve as a benchmark for us to calculate deviation from. For example, single level aggregations will show us what the mean and Standard deviation for each provider, city, state and disease group is. From this we can calculate deviations for observation in that specific provider, city, state and DRG. Similarly, dual level aggregations will give us more granular benchmarks.

Calculating Deviation Measures¶

We left-join the benchmark statistics to our dataframe to enable calculation of deviation measures

Using the benchmark statistics we have calculated so far, for each observation we created a measure of deviation defined as the number of standard deviations above/below the mean.

Deviation measure is defined as follows:

Deviation of specific variable for a specific observaion = [ Observed Value - Mean Value ] / Standard Deviation

This deviation, similar to a Z-score, can be calculated at the level of each aggregation identified previously. The naming convention followed is straightforward:

All deviation measures start with dev_ followed by the aggregation level (provider or state or DRG and so on) and end with the variable name (td or mp or mbc and so on). For example,

  • dev_provider_td : Deviation of total discharge from the benchmark for this provider
  • dev_DRG_mbc : Deviation of the ratio of medicare payments to covered charges for this specific DRG
In [9]:
#Creating deviation measures ( abs(value - mean)/std deviation)
#deviation measure for provider mean and drg and state median
data1['dev_provider_oop'] = (data1['average_pocket_payments'] - data1['median_provider_oop'])/data1['sd_provider_oop']
data1['dev_provider_mbc'] = (data1['medicare_by_covered'] - data1['median_provider_mbc'])/data1['sd_provider_mbc']
data1['dev_provider_mp'] = (data1['average_medicare_payments'] - data1['median_provider_mp'])/data1['sd_provider_mp']
data1['dev_provider_td'] = (data1['total_discharges'] - data1['median_provider_td'])/data1['sd_provider_td'] 
data1['dev_provider_mbt']= (data1['medicare_by_total'] - data1['median_provider_mbt']) / data1['sd_provider_mbt']

data1['dev_state_oop'] = (data1['average_pocket_payments'] - data1['median_state_oop'])/data1['sd_state_oop']
data1['dev_state_mbc'] = (data1['medicare_by_covered'] - data1['median_state_mbc'])/data1['sd_state_mbc']
data1['dev_state_mp'] = (data1['average_medicare_payments'] - data1['median_state_mp'])/data1['sd_state_mp']
data1['dev_state_td'] = (data1['total_discharges'] - data1['median_state_td'])/data1['sd_state_td'] 
data1['dev_state_mbt']= (data1['medicare_by_total'] - data1['median_state_mbt']) / data1['sd_state_mbt']

data1['dev_city_oop'] = (data1['average_pocket_payments'] - data1['median_city_oop'])/data1['sd_city_oop']
data1['dev_city_mbc'] = (data1['medicare_by_covered'] - data1['median_city_mbc'])/data1['sd_city_mbc']
data1['dev_city_mp'] = (data1['average_medicare_payments'] - data1['median_city_mp'])/data1['sd_city_mp']
data1['dev_city_td'] = (data1['total_discharges'] - data1['median_city_td'])/data1['sd_city_td'] 
data1['dev_city_mbt']= (data1['medicare_by_total'] - data1['median_city_mbt']) / data1['sd_city_mbt']

data1['dev_drg_oop'] = (data1['average_pocket_payments'] - data1['median_drg_oop'])/data1['sd_drg_oop']
data1['dev_drg_mbc'] = (data1['medicare_by_covered'] - data1['median_drg_mbc'])/data1['sd_drg_mbc']
data1['dev_drg_mp'] = (data1['average_medicare_payments'] - data1['median_drg_mp'])/data1['sd_drg_mp']
data1['dev_drg_td'] = (data1['total_discharges'] - data1['median_drg_td'])/data1['sd_drg_td'] 
data1['dev_drg_mbt']= (data1['medicare_by_total'] - data1['median_drg_mbt']) / data1['sd_drg_mbt']

#deviation measure for drg and state
data1['dev_drg_state_oop'] = (data1['average_pocket_payments'] - data1['median_drg_state_oop'])/data1['sd_drg_state_oop']
data1['dev_drg_state_mbc'] = (data1['medicare_by_covered'] - data1['median_drg_state_mbc'])/data1['sd_drg_state_mbc']
data1['dev_drg_state_mp'] = (data1['average_medicare_payments'] - data1['median_drg_state_mp'])/data1['sd_drg_state_mp']
data1['dev_drg_state_td'] = (data1['total_discharges'] - data1['median_drg_state_td'])/data1['sd_drg_state_td'] 
data1['dev_drg_state_mbt']= (data1['medicare_by_total'] - data1['median_drg_state_mbt']) / data1['sd_drg_state_mbt']

#deviation measure for drg and hospital referral group
data1['dev_drg_rfg_oop'] = (data1['average_pocket_payments'] - data1['median_drg_rfg_oop'])/data1['sd_drg_rfg_oop']
data1['dev_drg_rfg_mbc'] = (data1['medicare_by_covered'] - data1['median_drg_rfg_mbc'])/data1['sd_drg_rfg_mbc']
data1['dev_drg_rfg_mp'] = (data1['average_medicare_payments'] - data1['median_drg_rfg_mp'])/data1['sd_drg_rfg_mp']
data1['dev_drg_rfg_td'] = (data1['total_discharges'] - data1['median_drg_rfg_td'])/data1['sd_drg_rfg_td'] 
data1['dev_drg_rfg_mbt']= (data1['medicare_by_total'] - data1['median_drg_rfg_mbt']) / data1['sd_drg_rfg_mbt']

With these new features we have a measure of the number of standard deviations from the mean for:

  • average medicare payments
  • Total Discharges
  • average out of pocket payment
  • Ratio of medicare payment to covered charges
  • Ration of medicare payment to total payment

For each of these, we have deviations from mean at the level of :

  • Provider
  • Disease Group
  • State
  • City
  • Disease group by each state
  • Disease group by each hospital referral region

Unsupervised Clustering¶

Before we use pyOD to identify outliers, we will attempt to cluster these observations on the basis of the available data. This serves two purposes:

  1. Reducing the number of observations which need to be examined manually
  2. Provide a model for identifying fraudulent transaction as they happen

Setting up KNN for outlier identification¶

We performed the following steps to prepare for KNN based outlier detection:

  • Setup a model with default paramaters
  • Plotted a histogram using our earlier clusters to explore any overlaps
  • Examined features and scores across clusters
In [45]:

In [46]:
#setting up the model
clf_name = 'knn'
clf = KNN()
clf.fit(data_model)
Out[46]:
KNN(algorithm='auto', contamination=0.1, leaf_size=30, method='largest',
  metric='minkowski', metric_params=None, n_jobs=1, n_neighbors=5, p=2,
  radius=1.0)

The KNN Algorithm is similar to the K-means algorithm, in that both focus on calculating euclidean distances and grouping observations which are closer together into the same group. However, While k-means calculates distances from the randomly selected centroids based on the number of required clusters, KNN calculates distances from the center of the entire group of observations. This helps us identify outliers which are far from the center of the group in the n-dimensional space and thereby identify outliers.

In [72]:
data_check['outlier_score'] = clf.decision_scores_

The outlier score is a measure of the distance from the center. Which means, the higher the score, the further outside the typical group the observation is. Reinforcing our earlier thought process, Cluster 0 and 4 have far more observations with a higher outlier score.

KNN with average outlier score of 4 models¶

While KNN is extremely useful in identifying outliers, the model is sensitive to the start position and the number of neighbours being used in the algorithm. The default uses 5-nearest neighbours. To build a more stable model, we attempt to build 4 different KNN models, and average the outlier score across all models. Including the default case model, we would have averaged across 5 models with K-values of: 10,50, 100, and 150.

In [81]:
#Attempting KNN with mutiple parameters to identify best stable model
from pyod.models.combination import aom, moa, average, maximization
from pyod.utils.utility import standardizer

#Standardize data 
#data_model = standardizer(data_model) #Already standardizd using sci-kit learn

#Testing a range of k-neighbours from 10 to 100 in steps of 10.

n_clf = 4
k_list = [10, 50, 100, 150]

#pre-emptive dataframe to store results
train_scores = np.zeros([data_model.shape[0], n_clf])
train_scores.shape

#Modeling
for i in range(n_clf):
  k = k_list[i]
  clf = KNN(n_neighbors=k, method='largest')
  clf.fit(data_model)

  #Store results in each column
  train_scores[:, i] = clf.decision_scores_

#Normalizing scores
train_scores_norm = standardizer(train_scores)

With a more stable model, we identified twice the number of outliers which is still a low number considering it is less than 0.5% of the observations. Let us attempt the same using a different algorithm in the next section.

pyOD using PCA¶

In the last section, we attempted to build an outlier identifier model using a distance based methods - KNN. In this section, we will attempt to build a model using Principal Components Analysis. PCA is not a distance-based algorithm. Instead it attempts to implode a large number of components into fewer components by combining multiple features into components which are orthogonal to each other. PCA selects for the number of principal components which explain most of the variance.

We will attempt to build multiple models by varying the number of selected components in the model, ranging from 2 to 12.

In [43]:
from pyod.models.pca import PCA

#Setting up the model
n_sel = [2, 4, 6, 8, 10, 12]

#setting up an empty dataframe for labels 
train_labels = np.zeros([data_model.shape[0], 6])
train_labels.shape

#importing packages
#from pyod.models.pca import PCA

#Modeling 
i = 0
for n in n_sel:
  model = PCA(n_selected_components= n)
  model.fit(data_model)
  #store results in each column
  train_labels[:, i] = model.labels_
  i = i + 1
In [44]:
for i in range(6):
  coltitle = "PCA_model" + str(i)
  data_check[coltitle] = train_labels[:, i]

Now that we have built the models and stored the labels in our dataframe for checking the results, let us look at the models with 2 components and 12 components below.
